            <h2>The spark</h2>

            <p>In late 2013, the United Nations (<abbr>UN</abbr>) announced that 2015 would officially be the International Year of Light and Light-based technologies. The UN recognised the power of light, and aimed to raise global awareness about how light-based technologies can provide solutions to global challenges in energy, education, agriculture and health. From the day that the Year of Light was announced, plans began for events and projects across the world.</p>

            <blockquote>
            Light has revolutionized medicine, opened up international communication via the Internet, and continues to be central to linking cultural, economic and political aspects of the global society.
            </blockquote>

            <p>The announcement of that 2015 would be the Year of Light was greeted with excitement in St Andrews. Light is valued in the town; from the physicists in the Organic Semiconductor Optoelectronics research group through to the students lucky enough to catch the Northern Lights flickering over the cathedral on cool Scottish nights. Professor Robert Crawford saw opportunity within the announcement; opportunity to bring together the scientists whose discoveries are further lighting the world along with a photographer who documents the world through light and shadow, and a group of poets inspired by the two.</p>

